'''Owen''' was the perceived brother of [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] seen through a [[Force vision/Legends|vision]] from [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. In reality, Kenobi was actually seeing [[Owen Lars/Legends|Owen Lars]], [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker's]] stepbrother.

==History==
While [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]] was born to parents on the planet [[Stewjon/Legends|Stewjon]], he was identified as [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] as an infant and was quickly taken to the [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] for training in the ways of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] by the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]]. Despite this, during his apprenticeship to [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Qui-Gon Jinn/Legends|Qui-Gon Jinn]], Kenobi began having dreams of his parents and of a brother named Owen. Recounting his dreams to his master, Jinn cautioned him that dreams could sometimes be visions of the past or the future. For much of his life before the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], Kenobi believed that he must have returned to Stewjon early on and met his parents, thus forming the memory of them and his brother.<ref name="LW" />

It wasn't until the first few months of the Clone Wars when Kenobi learned that his [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]], [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], had met his stepbrother on [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]] in the days before he journeyed to [[Geonosis/Legends|Geonosis]]. After telling Kenobi of meeting Lars and learning of the death of his mother, [[Shmi Skywalker Lars/Legends|Shmi]], Kenobi began having doubts as to the true identity of his brother Owen. It wasn't until the end of the Clone Wars and the [[Great Jedi Purge/Legends|destruction of the Order]] that Kenobi began connecting all of the pieces of this decades-long puzzle. As he fled persecution on [[Nar Shaddaa/Legends|Nar Shaddaa]] with the infant [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] in his custody, Kenobi prepared to take the boy to the Lars Homestead on Tatooine. Finally, Kenobi concluded that the dreams he had as a boy were a vision of Owen Lars, his student's stepbrother. The fraternity he felt between himself and Owen was true, from a certain point of view. As Kenobi felt a brotherly bond with his former student, Lars too would be his brother.<ref name="LW" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Your mother and I knew he would find out eventually, but we wanted to keep you both as safe as possible, for as long as possible. So I took you to live with my brother Owen, on Tatooine&hellip;|Obi-Wan Kenobi’s ghost to Luke Skywalker in the ''Return of the Jedi'' novelization|<ref name="ROJN">[[Star Wars: Return of the Jedi (novelization)|''Star Wars Episode VI: Return of the Jedi'' novel]]</ref>}}
The idea that Obi-Wan Kenobi and [[Owen Lars/Legends|Owen Lars]], the adoptive uncle of [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]], were brothers, was introduced in the screenplay of the [[1983]] movie [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']], but did not make it in the final cut.<ref name="ERC">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref> The movie [[Star Wars: Return of the Jedi (novelization)|novelization]], however, did include a line in which Kenobi referred to "[his] brother Owen."<ref name="ROJN" /> Similarly, ''[[The Essential Guide to Characters]]'' said that Kenobi "does have at least one brother, Owen Lars"<ref name="EGTC">''[[The Essential Guide to Characters]]''</ref> and Owen Lars was explicitly described as the "brother of Obi-Wan Kenobi" in the [[Premiere Limited]] set of the [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game]] released by [[Decipher]] in [[1995]].<ref name="CCG">{{CCG|set=Premiere Limited|cardname=Owen Lars}}</ref> Said brother named Owen was later alluded to in the [[1999]] novel ''[[Jedi Apprentice: The Hidden Past]]'', during a dream of Kenobi's.<ref name="THP">''[[Jedi Apprentice: The Hidden Past]]''</ref> However, the [[2002]] movie [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']] revealed Luke's uncle as [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker's]] step-brother, rather than Kenobi's brother.<ref name="AOC">{{Film|II}}</ref> [[Abel G. Peña]]'s short story "[[Lone Wolf: A Tale of Obi-Wan and Luke]]," released online in [[2015]], resolved the seeming contradiction by making it clear that Lars was metaphorically like Obi-Wan’s brother, explaining Kenobi's dreams as a vision of his future, rather than a specter of his past.<ref name="LW" />

